00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:28.080
also what you like to do outside of work too.

00:03:29.600 --> 00:03:31.000
Hi everyone.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:32.839
Hopefully you can hear me.

00:03:32.839 --> 00:03:37.839
So it's Halloween, but also today

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:43.600
was our first global neurodiversity event here at Microsoft.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:49.320
And one of the common terms in the neurodiverse community

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:52.000
is masking.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:54.919
So you try and appear normal,

00:03:54.919 --> 00:03:57.880
you put on like that work face that you might be thinking,

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:02.039
you might put on on a grumpy day, but we do that generally.

00:04:02.039 --> 00:04:07.039
So we are unmasked or masked in my case for today.

00:04:07.479 --> 00:04:11.800
So that kind of leads me to the first thing.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:13.919
Hi everyone, I'm Steph, I'm autistic.

00:04:14.880 --> 00:04:19.880
And my day job here at Microsoft is to work with people,

00:04:20.720 --> 00:04:25.200
which is a fun challenge because people are irrational,

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:30.200
non-deterministic problems to help solve and understand.

00:04:30.880 --> 00:04:35.119
So it's an eternally challenging space for me to play in.

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:41.000
What we do, what myself and my team here do at Microsoft

00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:46.000
is we help our enterprise customers ship more value

00:04:47.239 --> 00:04:50.279
from their software and their AI solutions.

00:04:50.279 --> 00:04:52.959
So we help people make these things real

00:04:52.959 --> 00:04:57.279
and then get more and more value from them,

00:04:57.279 --> 00:04:59.399
which is a really cool job.

00:04:59.399 --> 00:05:01.839
Before that, before I joined Microsoft,

00:05:03.679 --> 00:05:08.640
I'd fallen a little bit into data science

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.880
from business intelligence and continuously wanting

00:05:11.880 --> 00:05:14.040
to do more, predict more.

00:05:14.040 --> 00:05:18.880
And that enabled me to use a lot of my math background

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:21.119
and see the value of statistics

00:05:21.119 --> 00:05:24.119
because I was always more of discrete maths and pure maths

00:05:24.119 --> 00:05:29.119
because what is 30 people on a chi-square physical table

00:05:29.399 --> 00:05:31.959
to look things up at, what's the point?

00:05:31.959 --> 00:05:33.959
So it was only when I was dealing with millions

00:05:33.959 --> 00:05:36.079
of customers that I saw the value

00:05:36.079 --> 00:05:39.160
in data science and statistics.

00:05:40.679 --> 00:05:42.920
Before I, just before I joined Microsoft,

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:46.679
I'd been running my own consultancy, locked data,

00:05:46.679 --> 00:05:51.679
and then tried doing a AI startup for manufacturers.

00:05:52.519 --> 00:05:56.480
And my biggest problem, aside of the fact that, you know,

00:05:56.480 --> 00:06:00.720
we went from half a million of pipe to zero pipe

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:02.799
in one day when COVID hit,

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:08.720
we went to, we had a nice, easy deploy to cloud button.

00:06:09.559 --> 00:06:13.320
And it turns out not a lot of manufacturers are, you know,

00:06:13.320 --> 00:06:15.880
doing that whole cloud thing just yet,

00:06:15.880 --> 00:06:20.000
especially in small, medium sized customers.

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:23.600
So I kept everybody going through COVID.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:25.359
And by the end of it,

00:06:25.359 --> 00:06:29.399
my bullet journal was meetings and emails.

00:06:29.399 --> 00:06:31.399
And we were doing a lot of services.

00:06:31.440 --> 00:06:33.200
So I went, you know what?

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:34.799
I'm not having fun anymore.

00:06:37.160 --> 00:06:41.399
And looked around for what my next step was.

00:06:41.399 --> 00:06:43.279
And that next step was building up

00:06:43.279 --> 00:06:45.640
my leadership capabilities

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:48.559
with a kind of a more robust foundation.

00:06:48.559 --> 00:06:50.279
So I joined Microsoft.

00:06:50.279 --> 00:06:53.799
And I've been able to be a grownup and get a house

00:06:53.799 --> 00:06:55.200
and pay off the student loan

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:57.079
and all those things that I postponed

00:06:57.079 --> 00:06:58.959
off running in my own business

00:06:59.559 --> 00:07:02.239
and keeping everybody paid before I paid myself.

00:07:02.239 --> 00:07:07.239
So it's fantastic to be here today

00:07:07.640 --> 00:07:11.720
because RStudio, the IDE,

00:07:11.720 --> 00:07:16.720
Posit as a company have been close to my heart

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:22.000
for 10 years now,

00:07:22.000 --> 00:07:24.880
I think 10 plus years I've been using RStudio.

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:30.559
And it really helps and things like R Markdown

00:07:30.559 --> 00:07:33.720
just completely transformed the way that I thought

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:37.519
about what good looks like in the data world.

00:07:37.519 --> 00:07:42.519
So it's been incredibly useful and transformational for me.

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:47.839
So I'm always glad to be here and talk to the Posit gang.

00:07:47.839 --> 00:07:49.040
Thank you, Steph.

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:51.839
I would love to hear a little bit about

00:07:51.839 --> 00:07:54.239
what you like to do in your free time, first of all.

00:07:54.359 --> 00:07:57.640
And then I would love to hear sort of how you got to data

00:07:57.640 --> 00:08:00.399
initially from maybe your background or what you studied.

00:08:00.399 --> 00:08:02.720
Cause I think you've got a degree in philosophy, right?

00:08:02.720 --> 00:08:06.160
And like that sort of transition from that to data

00:08:06.160 --> 00:08:08.600
feels really wide and it's probably full of fun stuff.

00:08:08.600 --> 00:08:10.200
So I'd love to hear about that.

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:13.640
And of course, like what you like to do outside of the job.

00:08:14.720 --> 00:08:17.799
So I'm very geeky, just generally.

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:21.760
So I really enjoy cooking, somewhat enjoy gardening

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:22.959
when I wanna go outside.

00:08:24.239 --> 00:08:28.600
But I read on average a fiction book a day.

00:08:30.519 --> 00:08:32.599
Like I wake up at seven o'clock in the morning.

00:08:32.599 --> 00:08:34.440
My partner won't get up till eight.

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:38.280
So I get an hour reading in before I even get out of bed.

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:42.200
I also do a bit of video gaming

00:08:42.200 --> 00:08:45.840
and like tabletop RPGs and stuff.

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:50.840
But also like to go out, experience good food, travel.

00:08:51.719 --> 00:08:55.799
And I've always used conferences as a great way

00:08:55.799 --> 00:08:58.359
to work out where to go in the world

00:08:58.359 --> 00:09:00.239
because it's so hard to pick.

00:09:00.239 --> 00:09:03.159
So if somebody gives me T and E to go somewhere,

00:09:03.159 --> 00:09:04.559
I'm gonna go there.

00:09:04.559 --> 00:09:06.359
T and E being travel and expenses.

00:09:08.799 --> 00:09:12.919
In terms of how did I get into data science

00:09:14.320 --> 00:09:15.799
and data generally?

00:09:15.799 --> 00:09:20.799
So I was being very kind of,

00:09:20.880 --> 00:09:23.359
maths and science oriented.

00:09:25.400 --> 00:09:28.359
When I was 16, I first tried my hand

00:09:28.359 --> 00:09:33.280
at kind of building a business idea.

00:09:33.280 --> 00:09:37.799
My boss at the time had and learned PHP,

00:09:37.799 --> 00:09:39.239
cross-browser compatibility

00:09:39.239 --> 00:09:41.679
and front-end development was not for me.

00:09:42.679 --> 00:09:44.320
That way lay ulcers.

00:09:44.919 --> 00:09:49.919
But then I did various things.

00:09:51.320 --> 00:09:54.679
I didn't actually go to university

00:09:54.679 --> 00:09:57.440
during my final two years of my degree.

00:09:57.440 --> 00:10:01.479
I worked full time and because it was philosophy,

00:10:01.479 --> 00:10:05.840
I just kind of read and wrote essays in the evenings

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:08.799
so I could pay all my bills and things.

00:10:08.799 --> 00:10:12.640
And I got a job as a product analyst.

00:10:12.679 --> 00:10:17.080
We were, as my boss said, we were the new handbag.

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:18.840
Everybody had to have an analyst.

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:24.119
And I did things from schmoozing

00:10:24.119 --> 00:10:27.640
and doing karaoke with journalists

00:10:27.640 --> 00:10:32.520
through to negotiating contracts with energy suppliers

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:36.239
through to automating sales spreadsheets

00:10:36.239 --> 00:10:40.599
and doing forecasting and using all my Excel skills,

00:10:40.599 --> 00:10:44.000
using the buy a book scheme

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.640
to basically read every single book Mr. Excel

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:51.640
had ever written to write BBA and things like that.

00:10:52.799 --> 00:10:57.799
And I just, I really enjoyed the enabling other people

00:10:59.640 --> 00:11:02.799
and solving problems and helping people

00:11:02.799 --> 00:11:05.880
do a better, make better decisions.

00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:10.479
So I convinced somebody to teach me SQL

00:11:11.359 --> 00:11:13.080
and then after learning some SQL,

00:11:13.080 --> 00:11:16.799
I learned SQL server reporting services

00:11:16.799 --> 00:11:18.200
and integration services.

00:11:18.200 --> 00:11:21.239
And I still have flashbacks of doing string conversions

00:11:21.239 --> 00:11:23.919
between my SQL and SQL server.

00:11:25.880 --> 00:11:30.880
And probably the first data science type activity

00:11:31.919 --> 00:11:36.919
that I actually did was using SQL server analysis services

00:11:37.599 --> 00:11:39.760
to do propensity analysis.

00:11:40.280 --> 00:11:42.479
Who would buy different types of insurance?

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:46.919
So I just kind of kept going from there.

00:11:48.119 --> 00:11:50.599
I'm very community taught in everything

00:11:50.599 --> 00:11:53.679
and I try to give back to the community as a result.

00:11:53.679 --> 00:11:57.919
But yeah, I've picked up so much over the years

00:11:57.919 --> 00:12:02.080
and learned and I keep going where my passion takes me.

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:04.400
Thank you so much, Steph.

00:12:04.400 --> 00:12:09.400
So I know I had first reached out to you,

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.679
I think it was maybe a little over a month ago.

00:12:13.679 --> 00:12:17.320
And so Hadley had reached out to me and said,

00:12:17.320 --> 00:12:20.119
had I had any hangouts around the idea

00:12:20.119 --> 00:12:22.599
of how do you persuade your manager

00:12:22.599 --> 00:12:25.479
to give you more time to be a better programmer?

00:12:25.479 --> 00:12:30.239
And he highly recommended your Earl conference keynote.

00:12:30.320 --> 00:12:32.159
And so I thought it'd be great to chat

00:12:32.159 --> 00:12:33.479
a little bit about that here.

00:12:33.479 --> 00:12:36.039
So what advice do you have for someone

00:12:36.039 --> 00:12:38.320
who wants to persuade their manager

00:12:38.320 --> 00:12:41.119
to give more time to improve their skills?

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:47.320
Yeah, I always remember a quote that I think

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:49.159
gets attributed to various people

00:12:49.159 --> 00:12:51.320
but includes Abraham Lincoln,

00:12:51.320 --> 00:12:56.320
which is if I had six hours to cut down a tree,

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:59.119
I'd spend four hours sharpening my axe.

00:13:01.239 --> 00:13:06.239
And a side of kind of growing my skills

00:13:06.440 --> 00:13:08.719
and financial services and that teaching me

00:13:08.719 --> 00:13:10.080
to want to always be right,

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
the competencies with which we can execute

00:13:18.479 --> 00:13:22.559
directly impact the time that we can do something

00:13:22.559 --> 00:13:24.799
and the quality by which we can do something.

00:13:24.799 --> 00:13:28.039
So if we are not well equipped,

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:30.799
not well equipped if our axes are blunt,

00:13:30.799 --> 00:13:34.200
it's gonna take us six hours to chop down that tree.

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:36.000
And then it's gonna take us six hours

00:13:36.000 --> 00:13:38.239
to chop down that next tree.

00:13:38.239 --> 00:13:42.719
But if you spend that four hours sharpening the axe,

00:13:42.719 --> 00:13:45.080
it takes two hours to cut down the first tree,

00:13:45.080 --> 00:13:47.280
two hours to cut down the next tree.

00:13:47.280 --> 00:13:49.559
And if you keep sharpening for five, 10 minutes

00:13:49.559 --> 00:13:52.320
in between each tree, it's only two and a half,

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:55.440
it's like less than two and a half hours per tree.

00:13:55.440 --> 00:13:57.840
So that's the way I look at things.

00:13:58.679 --> 00:14:03.280
And talk to managers about is, and leaders is that

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:09.400
when we don't have time to hone our craft

00:14:09.880 --> 00:14:14.880
to deliver quality and to deliver quality work,

00:14:17.280 --> 00:14:22.280
we end up paying far more time in maintenance efforts

00:14:22.559 --> 00:14:25.239
and doing things in subpar ways.

00:14:25.239 --> 00:14:28.840
So it can feel slower at first,

00:14:28.840 --> 00:14:33.000
but you're going slower to go fast, longer term.

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:37.000
Competency and quality baked into everything we do

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:41.760
enables more innovation in the long term.

00:14:45.599 --> 00:14:46.640
Thank you so much.

00:14:46.640 --> 00:14:51.039
I wanted to follow up with another thing

00:14:51.039 --> 00:14:54.599
that was like, Steph wrote about this and talked about this

00:14:54.599 --> 00:14:58.440
and it's really important, which is the BAU article.

00:14:58.440 --> 00:15:01.080
And I didn't even know what BAU was

00:15:01.080 --> 00:15:02.280
before I read that article.

00:15:02.280 --> 00:15:03.440
I was like, what is this?

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:05.119
And then everyone told me that this is a thing.

00:15:05.119 --> 00:15:06.559
Everybody knows that acronym, but I didn't.

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:11.559
So the topic of it is that BAU is choking development.

00:15:12.159 --> 00:15:14.799
And I would love to hear a little bit more about that.

00:15:16.400 --> 00:15:21.400
Yeah, so I was really glad to finally write that article

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:26.200
because it's been something that stuck with me for years

00:15:26.200 --> 00:15:29.840
is you see people who,

00:15:30.840 --> 00:15:34.799
when they don't necessarily have time

00:15:34.799 --> 00:15:39.799
to invest in doing things in a way that keeps quality,

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:43.799
that's gonna have high quality

00:15:43.799 --> 00:15:47.840
and low maintainability requirements

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:51.719
and is easy to extend and create new things.

00:15:51.719 --> 00:15:53.960
When people aren't doing that,

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:57.559
anything they ship is going to then cost them

00:15:57.559 --> 00:15:59.479
more time to do something,

00:15:59.479 --> 00:16:02.320
to look after whatever they've shipped.

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:05.479
That then gives them less time to ship the next thing.

00:16:06.400 --> 00:16:09.280
So the next thing takes longer to deliver.

00:16:09.280 --> 00:16:13.039
And then they also have to do the maintenance on that thing.

00:16:13.039 --> 00:16:14.520
And as they keep going,

00:16:14.520 --> 00:16:16.640
they spend more and more of their time

00:16:17.640 --> 00:16:20.640
kind of like hugging, loving, maintaining.

00:16:22.559 --> 00:16:24.200
Sorry, I'm in the office today

00:16:24.200 --> 00:16:27.520
and it looks like the lights have gone off.

00:16:28.479 --> 00:16:29.320
There we go.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.320
So I just have to go and wave around the office like a loon.

00:16:34.440 --> 00:16:39.440
Yeah, so the amount of continued efforts

00:16:39.960 --> 00:16:43.880
something takes after you initially develop it

00:16:43.919 --> 00:16:48.119
for it to continue being useful to other people

00:16:49.119 --> 00:16:52.520
takes up your time away from building

00:16:52.520 --> 00:16:54.520
the next new useful thing.

00:16:55.719 --> 00:17:00.520
And it's slowly but surely stacks up and stacks up

00:17:00.520 --> 00:17:03.840
until the only thing you're able to do with your day

00:17:03.840 --> 00:17:05.400
is maintain things.

00:17:06.439 --> 00:17:11.439
And most people don't get into their jobs

00:17:12.319 --> 00:17:15.719
to be maintainers for systems.

00:17:15.719 --> 00:17:19.920
They get into their jobs to build great things

00:17:19.920 --> 00:17:22.160
and add value.

00:17:24.439 --> 00:17:27.800
And it's really hard to feel like you're adding value

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:31.479
when you're just keeping all your previous work going.

00:17:32.719 --> 00:17:35.000
So what we can do is,

00:17:35.000 --> 00:17:37.680
and this comes down to your question of,

00:17:37.920 --> 00:17:42.920
convincing people to have that time for learning.

00:17:44.199 --> 00:17:49.199
It also comes down to how do we design things

00:17:50.479 --> 00:17:53.319
and work and how do we work

00:17:53.319 --> 00:17:57.040
so that the thing that we output at the end

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:02.040
is gonna take less time to keep it adding value.

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:06.359
Because the less time that we can make that take,

00:18:06.400 --> 00:18:08.719
the more new things we can build

00:18:08.719 --> 00:18:11.160
and the more things that we can support

00:18:11.160 --> 00:18:12.599
for the same amount of time.

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:15.719
And so that's something that we all need

00:18:15.719 --> 00:18:17.760
to be thinking about is,

00:18:17.760 --> 00:18:21.560
are you currently spending too much time

00:18:21.560 --> 00:18:24.439
just keeping the lights on and putting out fires?

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:31.280
With a bit of time, could you get that time burden down?

00:18:31.599 --> 00:18:33.839
Could you improve your situation?

00:18:33.839 --> 00:18:36.560
And could you change the way that you do things

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:40.599
so that you spend less time going forward

00:18:40.599 --> 00:18:44.160
on that maintenance, on those activities?

00:18:44.160 --> 00:18:49.079
Because those activities aren't adding value,

00:18:49.079 --> 00:18:50.760
adding new value,

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:55.000
they're just hopefully keeping old value continuing.

00:18:59.199 --> 00:19:00.839
Thank you so much, Seth.

