00:19:16.479 --> 00:19:19.800
Steph, to dive a little bit deeper

00:19:19.800 --> 00:19:22.079
into some of the work you're doing at Microsoft,

00:19:22.079 --> 00:19:24.040
would you be able to share a bit

00:19:24.040 --> 00:19:26.920
about some of the problems your team helps solve?

00:19:27.920 --> 00:19:32.920
Yeah, so I work primarily in software

00:19:36.040 --> 00:19:39.040
and the use of AI capabilities,

00:19:39.040 --> 00:19:42.839
but a lot of this still ends up being really relevant

00:19:42.839 --> 00:19:44.119
for data scientists.

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:49.439
So we focus on a number of areas,

00:19:49.439 --> 00:19:53.839
and one of them is what we'd call application modernization.

00:19:53.839 --> 00:19:56.040
Somebody built something a while ago,

00:19:57.400 --> 00:19:59.520
or in an enterprise,

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:02.000
lots of people have built things and bought things,

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:04.400
and they're all sitting there and running,

00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:07.280
but they all have technology

00:20:07.280 --> 00:20:10.359
that was current at the time they've employed

00:20:10.359 --> 00:20:14.479
and haven't necessarily had a lot of updates since.

00:20:14.479 --> 00:20:17.640
And they're going into those kind of maintenance problems

00:20:17.640 --> 00:20:22.160
of either people just spending all their time

00:20:22.160 --> 00:20:26.680
maintaining things and not shipping value for the company.

00:20:27.680 --> 00:20:30.719
Or everybody's stopped maintaining things,

00:20:30.719 --> 00:20:32.160
and there's a whole bunch of fires

00:20:32.160 --> 00:20:34.599
that people are desperately going,

00:20:34.599 --> 00:20:36.400
not me, don't make me fix it.

00:20:37.640 --> 00:20:42.119
So we start working with customers to think,

00:20:43.160 --> 00:20:48.160
okay, how can you change your perceptions

00:20:49.839 --> 00:20:52.640
around people and processes to solve these?

00:20:52.640 --> 00:20:55.000
Because it's always a people problem.

00:20:55.040 --> 00:20:57.079
Processes support people,

00:20:57.079 --> 00:20:59.079
and then tools support processes.

00:20:59.079 --> 00:21:01.400
So it's how do you keep the culture

00:21:01.400 --> 00:21:04.400
of people, processes, peace first,

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:06.439
but then also how do you bring technology

00:21:06.439 --> 00:21:07.920
to help change things?

00:21:07.920 --> 00:21:12.400
So in the case of these app modernization scenarios,

00:21:12.400 --> 00:21:17.400
how can you use different tools as part of your processes

00:21:18.079 --> 00:21:20.599
to start bringing your technology

00:21:20.599 --> 00:21:23.040
up to a consistent baseline?

00:21:23.040 --> 00:21:25.760
Or how do you take a value-based approach

00:21:25.760 --> 00:21:29.199
to where do you drive these efforts and so on?

00:21:29.199 --> 00:21:34.079
So we work with a lot of customers on modernization.

00:21:34.079 --> 00:21:36.959
And this is in kind of the data world.

00:21:36.959 --> 00:21:39.560
This might be all databases.

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:42.079
You might have Hadoop clusters running

00:21:42.079 --> 00:21:44.560
with MapReduce jobs.

00:21:44.560 --> 00:21:47.479
You might have old versions of Python,

00:21:48.640 --> 00:21:52.160
like version two running and not version three.

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:56.040
And software, even when it is,

00:21:56.040 --> 00:22:00.839
every software ages and rusts and technology moves on.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:03.640
So that's one of the key areas.

00:22:03.640 --> 00:22:07.239
The other, we also help people build new things.

00:22:08.239 --> 00:22:10.520
Well, and better, and kind of think about,

00:22:10.520 --> 00:22:13.839
okay, how do you proactively optimize

00:22:13.839 --> 00:22:18.839
and how do you make sure you've got great observability

00:22:19.119 --> 00:22:21.520
and monitoring to know it's working

00:22:22.160 --> 00:22:23.199
and things.

00:22:23.199 --> 00:22:26.719
And then the final area that we do a lot of work with

00:22:26.719 --> 00:22:30.079
is how does your team

00:22:32.160 --> 00:22:35.199
use, have the right processes and tools

00:22:35.199 --> 00:22:37.599
to continue shipping value?

00:22:37.599 --> 00:22:39.680
So some of you might have heard

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.640
Microsoft has a lot of co-pilots.

00:22:44.199 --> 00:22:46.160
I'm proud of myself, it's only 24,

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:47.839
it's 24 whole minutes in,

00:22:47.839 --> 00:22:50.400
and that's the first time I said the word co-pilot.

00:22:51.719 --> 00:22:56.719
But we have GitHub co-pilots

00:22:56.760 --> 00:23:01.160
to help developers, data scientists, data engineers,

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:08.959
kind of get some of the grunt work of writing code

00:23:08.959 --> 00:23:10.520
that makes a difference,

00:23:13.520 --> 00:23:15.800
quicker and more effective.

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:20.800
So how technology teams

00:23:22.520 --> 00:23:27.520
provision environments for data scientists,

00:23:27.800 --> 00:23:30.119
developers to work in,

00:23:30.119 --> 00:23:34.239
what does that look like for third parties and contractors?

00:23:34.239 --> 00:23:37.280
What about when you have like a Java estate

00:23:37.280 --> 00:23:39.920
and a .NET estate and a Spark estate

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:44.920
and like all of these disparate development stacks?

00:23:46.079 --> 00:23:48.319
How do you work and enable somebody

00:23:48.319 --> 00:23:50.800
to switch from all of those?

00:23:50.920 --> 00:23:53.800
How do you build a consistent compliance

00:23:53.800 --> 00:23:57.319
and security backbone automated

00:23:57.319 --> 00:24:01.599
inside your development and collaboration environment

00:24:01.599 --> 00:24:04.880
like GitHub or GitLab and things?

00:24:04.880 --> 00:24:09.400
And so we help customers tackle these types of problems

00:24:09.400 --> 00:24:14.400
because there's no silver bullet on any of this.

00:24:14.680 --> 00:24:18.119
It's all kind of hard work,

00:24:18.119 --> 00:24:23.119
doing culture and process work to enable people

00:24:23.520 --> 00:24:24.520
as well as tools.

00:24:27.319 --> 00:24:28.520
Thanks, Steph.

00:24:28.520 --> 00:24:31.000
I just thought of a follow-up question

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:31.839
I meant to ask you

00:24:31.839 --> 00:24:35.599
when we're talking about business as usual work.

00:24:36.959 --> 00:24:39.560
I think about this sometimes with like doing things

00:24:39.560 --> 00:24:43.199
that I'm just, they just do because I've always done it.

00:24:43.199 --> 00:24:46.040
Can you tell us a little bit about like how an initiative

00:24:46.040 --> 00:24:49.640
that you've killed or how you go about doing that

00:24:49.640 --> 00:24:51.319
or deciding when it's right?

00:24:53.280 --> 00:24:57.839
Yeah, so I very proudly, I'm very happy to say

00:24:57.839 --> 00:25:01.119
that in Microsoft, which can have a culture

00:25:01.119 --> 00:25:04.959
of you need to own things, I've killed two things,

00:25:04.959 --> 00:25:08.520
two of my babies this year, this fiscal year.

00:25:09.439 --> 00:25:14.439
And it really helps to be able to kill something

00:25:17.079 --> 00:25:19.680
when you have had a solid definition of death.

00:25:21.079 --> 00:25:24.800
So like with everything, it is amazing

00:25:24.800 --> 00:25:27.319
if you can get clarity on what good looks like

00:25:28.680 --> 00:25:31.640
and especially when you're thinking about software

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:35.040
or processes or new initiatives.

00:25:35.040 --> 00:25:38.040
So one of the things that I killed

00:25:41.520 --> 00:25:46.359
is we have discovery processes

00:25:46.359 --> 00:25:51.359
to help different parts of customers' estate

00:25:51.359 --> 00:25:53.280
whether it's their infrastructure, their data,

00:25:53.280 --> 00:25:55.920
their data science or their applications,

00:25:55.920 --> 00:25:59.359
be able to understand where their technical data is

00:25:59.359 --> 00:26:02.880
and what the value is that they're going to be able to get

00:26:02.880 --> 00:26:03.719
in the cloud.

00:26:04.680 --> 00:26:09.680
We inherited this activity when we got created

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:12.599
as a new team last year.

00:26:13.560 --> 00:26:18.199
And so I formed an initiative to help us be able

00:26:18.199 --> 00:26:22.839
to onboard this new capability, help us learn quickly,

00:26:22.839 --> 00:26:25.920
share best, share good practices.

00:26:25.920 --> 00:26:27.880
I try not to call them best practices,

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:32.719
share good practices and be able to like really embed this

00:26:32.719 --> 00:26:35.640
as part of our kind of commitment to excellence.

00:26:37.479 --> 00:26:40.959
By the time a year had rolled on,

00:26:42.079 --> 00:26:45.560
we had learned everything we needed to learn

00:26:45.560 --> 00:26:50.560
as a broader group, the enablement had happened

00:26:50.599 --> 00:26:55.599
and people were kind of rolling well or rolling all right.

00:26:57.640 --> 00:27:02.640
But then the bits that were still a challenge

00:27:03.719 --> 00:27:06.920
wasn't really something that we could do centrally.

00:27:07.839 --> 00:27:12.839
It needed distributed efforts.

00:27:13.599 --> 00:27:16.520
So I killed the central piece

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:21.520
because I was able to line up accountable people elsewhere

00:27:22.959 --> 00:27:25.640
who were thinking about things from the infrastructure side,

00:27:25.640 --> 00:27:27.199
the data side, the app side,

00:27:28.520 --> 00:27:31.040
for them to be able to go and actually go,

00:27:31.040 --> 00:27:33.239
okay, so we're good at this.

00:27:34.119 --> 00:27:37.319
What does great look like for us

00:27:37.319 --> 00:27:40.640
when we do the input piece, the data piece?

00:27:40.640 --> 00:27:43.800
And so now that I killed the central piece

00:27:43.800 --> 00:27:48.800
because I was able to put it into different activities,

00:27:50.079 --> 00:27:52.800
other initiatives that are running

00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:55.280
because those are gonna be able to take things

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:56.359
to the next level.

00:27:56.359 --> 00:27:59.599
So my definition of done, get everybody equipped

00:27:59.599 --> 00:28:03.119
and enabled to execute was sorted.

00:28:04.280 --> 00:28:06.560
And now other people are responsible

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:09.560
for driving their individual areas of excellence.

