00:32:58.199 --> 00:33:01.880
to a lot of the heavier data science and tech stuff

00:33:01.880 --> 00:33:03.719
that I was previously doing.

00:33:04.599 --> 00:33:05.439
Yeah, for sure.

00:33:05.439 --> 00:33:10.439
I will put my email address in the chat.

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:12.479
And anybody who wants to connect with me

00:33:12.479 --> 00:33:15.880
for this kind of thing can email me

00:33:15.880 --> 00:33:19.319
and I will endeavor to connect you with the right person

00:33:19.319 --> 00:33:20.920
or chat with you myself about it.

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:25.439
Because yeah, AI ethics is something

00:33:25.439 --> 00:33:30.239
that incredibly matters and is one of the reasons

00:33:30.239 --> 00:33:31.959
why I'm proud to work at Microsoft.

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:35.040
Because we have been,

00:33:36.680 --> 00:33:39.680
like we do things like pushing for legislation,

00:33:39.680 --> 00:33:43.800
which how many tech companies push for legislation

00:33:46.239 --> 00:33:47.079
of themselves?

00:33:47.079 --> 00:33:50.760
Like that kind of thing is just an amazing situation

00:33:50.760 --> 00:33:51.599
to be in.

00:33:51.599 --> 00:33:55.880
So yeah, well, very happy to connect offline.

00:33:55.880 --> 00:33:56.719
That's awesome, Steph.

00:33:56.719 --> 00:33:57.560
Thank you.

00:33:57.560 --> 00:33:58.560
That's very generous of you.

00:33:58.880 --> 00:34:01.359
I saw, I wanted to bring in Kylie,

00:34:01.359 --> 00:34:03.839
because Kylie, you asked a question way, way, way

00:34:03.839 --> 00:34:06.160
in the beginning and we missed it.

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:07.280
Would you like to ask?

00:34:07.280 --> 00:34:08.959
And we're all talking about it in chat, by the way.

00:34:08.959 --> 00:34:10.879
So everybody weigh in.

00:34:13.879 --> 00:34:14.719
Sure.

00:34:15.800 --> 00:34:18.520
Sorry, I can't turn on my camera at the moment.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:20.560
But Steph, at the very beginning, you said,

00:34:20.560 --> 00:34:22.879
you're into cooking, you read a book a day.

00:34:22.879 --> 00:34:25.439
And so my natural question is,

00:34:25.439 --> 00:34:27.000
what's one of the favorite things

00:34:27.560 --> 00:34:30.280
what's one of the favorite books you've read recently?

00:34:32.320 --> 00:34:35.080
Or not recently, you know, whatever comes to mind.

00:34:37.120 --> 00:34:39.840
I'll give you my latest nonfiction.

00:34:39.840 --> 00:34:44.840
So I have been incredibly inspired

00:34:46.760 --> 00:34:49.919
and enriched by Brené Pax's work.

00:34:50.919 --> 00:34:52.719
So I read Daring Greatly,

00:34:53.719 --> 00:34:56.399
which has really helped me think about

00:34:59.840 --> 00:35:04.560
even things like the shame I feel around my gender

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:07.639
and how I communicate in my relationships,

00:35:07.639 --> 00:35:10.280
but also how I show up as a leader.

00:35:11.679 --> 00:35:14.800
And that then led me to read a theme

00:35:14.800 --> 00:35:18.800
working through her Atlas of the Heart,

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:22.199
which is a book on emotions of experiences.

00:35:23.520 --> 00:35:28.520
Because I have pretty pants recognition

00:35:29.879 --> 00:35:32.919
of what's going on in my body and my emotions.

00:35:32.919 --> 00:35:35.959
So kind of having some actual effectively

00:35:35.959 --> 00:35:40.479
textbook definitions and anecdotes and experiences

00:35:40.479 --> 00:35:43.560
of like, this is what sadness is like for a lot of people.

00:35:43.560 --> 00:35:46.959
This is, you know, this is positive comparison

00:35:46.959 --> 00:35:48.520
and this is negative, you know,

00:35:48.520 --> 00:35:51.560
this is like when it goes into unhealthy.

00:35:51.600 --> 00:35:55.439
So it's been useful for giving me better vocabulary

00:35:56.399 --> 00:35:58.239
and therefore a better personality.

00:36:00.560 --> 00:36:01.879
Thank you, that's awesome.

00:36:01.879 --> 00:36:04.360
Yeah, anything by Brené Brown is amazing.

00:36:04.360 --> 00:36:06.679
And actually even hard for me to read sometimes

00:36:06.679 --> 00:36:08.639
because it brings up heavy stuff and I'm like,

00:36:08.639 --> 00:36:11.199
oh, I'm having a hard time getting through this.

00:36:11.199 --> 00:36:14.199
Well, we had a great, great question on Slido

00:36:14.199 --> 00:36:15.399
that I would love to ask.

00:36:15.399 --> 00:36:17.239
It says, I feel that as a coder,

00:36:17.239 --> 00:36:19.679
I can't progress further in my career

00:36:19.679 --> 00:36:21.320
without going into management.

00:36:22.040 --> 00:36:24.439
I think that we all experience this at some point.

00:36:24.439 --> 00:36:25.879
Any tips for progression,

00:36:25.879 --> 00:36:30.040
but wanting to stay at the coding level?

00:36:33.040 --> 00:36:38.040
So I think the problem in many organizations

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:43.320
is actually people go in management's frame

00:36:44.959 --> 00:36:47.439
as the way to have more influence.

00:36:48.439 --> 00:36:53.439
So, you know, you can have leadership without authority

00:36:54.760 --> 00:36:57.639
and as a technical person,

00:36:57.639 --> 00:37:02.639
what that often looks like is to a certain extent,

00:37:03.080 --> 00:37:08.080
moving away from being excellent at the coding side

00:37:08.919 --> 00:37:13.919
to becoming a deciding factor in what gets coded.

00:37:14.520 --> 00:37:19.520
So this is, you know, how do you,

00:37:19.600 --> 00:37:24.600
things like architectural design, what do we research?

00:37:24.840 --> 00:37:26.719
What do we invest our time in?

00:37:26.719 --> 00:37:30.520
All of these things, kind of some organizations

00:37:30.520 --> 00:37:32.760
conflate with management,

00:37:32.760 --> 00:37:35.679
but they're technical leadership pieces.

00:37:35.679 --> 00:37:40.679
And so you can continue being an amazing coder

00:37:41.479 --> 00:37:46.479
for sure, but the challenge is,

00:37:47.800 --> 00:37:51.280
and some companies will push it as you can only progress

00:37:51.280 --> 00:37:53.719
if you have, if you go into management,

00:37:53.719 --> 00:37:57.959
but really the push is for you to go

00:37:57.959 --> 00:38:02.959
from being quite directed to directing.

00:38:03.800 --> 00:38:06.719
That's the setting strategy to having impact

00:38:06.719 --> 00:38:07.840
at a larger scale.

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:14.280
If you want to continue solving these technical problems

00:38:14.360 --> 00:38:16.520
or building new algorithms

00:38:16.520 --> 00:38:19.560
or kind of being on the technology cutting edge,

00:38:19.560 --> 00:38:21.239
there is nothing wrong with that.

00:38:22.479 --> 00:38:24.239
You can get amazingly good,

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:27.719
but there is a challenge.

00:38:27.719 --> 00:38:29.760
And I think that's the challenge.

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:30.959
You can get amazingly good,

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:36.000
but there are only certain types of organizations

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.120
that will respect those boundaries.

00:38:41.280 --> 00:38:44.239
And it's okay to have those as boundaries

00:38:44.239 --> 00:38:45.560
and continue doing them.

00:38:48.560 --> 00:38:53.040
But you might, for various reasons,

00:38:53.040 --> 00:38:55.080
prefer to think about how can I have

00:38:55.080 --> 00:38:56.560
a greater scale of impact?

00:38:57.560 --> 00:38:59.560
And that's where management

00:38:59.560 --> 00:39:02.320
or product management architecture,

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:05.879
various bits and pieces will evolve your role.

00:39:08.760 --> 00:39:09.600
Thank you.

00:39:09.600 --> 00:39:11.360
Yeah, I once had a director tell me,

00:39:12.360 --> 00:39:14.000
you'll be ready to go into management

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:15.679
when you start realizing that you want

00:39:15.679 --> 00:39:18.800
to make the decisions about how things go

00:39:18.800 --> 00:39:20.679
and you want that level of control.

00:39:21.560 --> 00:39:23.959
And I think that there's something to that.

00:39:24.959 --> 00:39:26.679
You know, I have another great one from Slido.

00:39:26.679 --> 00:39:28.040
How do you like...

00:39:28.040 --> 00:39:29.280
Oh, go ahead.

00:39:29.280 --> 00:39:32.120
Yeah, I was wondering if we could stay

00:39:32.120 --> 00:39:33.280
on this one a little bit,

00:39:33.280 --> 00:39:35.479
because I like the point you made

00:39:35.479 --> 00:39:40.479
about like going from being directed to directing.

00:39:40.679 --> 00:39:45.399
And do you have any tips for us on like how you do that?

00:39:45.399 --> 00:39:47.760
I know some of the things we've talked about before

00:39:47.760 --> 00:39:49.919
in other Hangouts is like,

00:39:49.919 --> 00:39:53.399
if you're not at that high leadership level,

00:39:53.399 --> 00:39:56.560
how do you get in the room for some of these conversations

00:39:56.560 --> 00:40:00.120
and how do you influence the decisions being made?

00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:06.399
Yeah, so part of it is,

00:40:06.399 --> 00:40:09.439
unfortunately, fortunately, people skills,

00:40:10.360 --> 00:40:15.080
but a large proportion of it is actually,

00:40:15.080 --> 00:40:17.120
how do you approach your job

00:40:17.120 --> 00:40:20.800
in terms of how are you scaling your impact?

00:40:20.800 --> 00:40:25.800
So, unfortunately, a whole lot of applications

00:40:28.840 --> 00:40:31.439
or machine learning solutions and everything

00:40:31.439 --> 00:40:35.800
are kind of like fundamentally the same.

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:37.560
You're gonna go through the same process,

00:40:37.560 --> 00:40:39.840
you're gonna write roughly the same code

00:40:39.840 --> 00:40:43.320
and it's gonna produce kind of roughly the same outputs.

00:40:44.479 --> 00:40:49.479
The way you can scale is,

00:40:50.479 --> 00:40:53.800
okay, how do we build the framework

00:40:53.800 --> 00:40:58.800
to stop people doing roughly the same thing

00:41:00.439 --> 00:41:03.000
bespoke every time?

00:41:03.000 --> 00:41:07.239
How do I change the way that we work

00:41:07.239 --> 00:41:10.800
to deliver more business value more quickly?

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:13.800
And then how do I tell people

00:41:13.800 --> 00:41:17.760
that we're having more business value more quickly?

00:41:17.879 --> 00:41:21.239
Because you can't just do it for the funsies,

00:41:21.239 --> 00:41:23.520
you need a measurement

00:41:23.520 --> 00:41:25.719
and you need to be able to communicate it

00:41:25.719 --> 00:41:27.760
in terms of like positive things.

00:41:29.040 --> 00:41:34.040
Alternatively, scaling out is one way of doing things.

00:41:36.320 --> 00:41:40.360
So like being able to automate the production,

00:41:40.360 --> 00:41:43.159
but there's also scaling up your impact.

00:41:43.159 --> 00:41:45.760
So you might build that one solution

00:41:47.760 --> 00:41:50.159
but then how do you make that one solution

00:41:50.159 --> 00:41:52.320
have more impact?

00:41:52.320 --> 00:41:54.120
Could it generalize

00:41:54.120 --> 00:41:57.399
to a slightly different part of the business?

00:41:57.399 --> 00:41:59.959
Could you publish the results?

00:41:59.959 --> 00:42:02.639
Do internal knowledge transfer?

00:42:02.639 --> 00:42:07.639
Could you help get that through regulatory sign-off processes

00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:10.679
when that's not currently your job?

00:42:10.679 --> 00:42:14.679
So you can think about how can you add more business value

00:42:15.679 --> 00:42:18.600
that is more strategically useful

00:42:19.679 --> 00:42:24.439
than the initial act of writing the code is useful.

00:42:24.439 --> 00:42:26.199
Because writing the code is useful,

00:42:27.080 --> 00:42:31.080
but it's kind of similar with research

00:42:31.080 --> 00:42:34.199
in that the act of research is useful,

00:42:34.199 --> 00:42:37.159
but almost until something has gone through

00:42:37.159 --> 00:42:40.239
its commercialization and commoditization phases

00:42:41.199 --> 00:42:43.879
and is turned into something practical.

00:42:45.080 --> 00:42:48.360
It's only that practical piece

00:42:48.360 --> 00:42:52.800
that proves the value of the research in many cases.

00:42:52.800 --> 00:42:57.600
And we might have some positive debates about that

00:42:57.600 --> 00:43:00.040
in my perspective on research,

00:43:01.679 --> 00:43:03.040
but it's the same kind of thing

00:43:03.040 --> 00:43:07.639
when we do a single activity in our work life.

00:43:07.639 --> 00:43:11.080
It's how you turn that one piece,

00:43:11.080 --> 00:43:14.199
that one-to-one time-to-value effort

00:43:14.199 --> 00:43:17.320
into a one-to-many value

00:43:18.399 --> 00:43:22.280
that you really start moving up the stack

00:43:22.280 --> 00:43:24.919
in terms of influence and perceived impact.

00:43:27.800 --> 00:43:29.399
That's awesome, thank you.

00:43:29.399 --> 00:43:31.360
I'm glad we stayed on that for a second.

00:43:32.360 --> 00:43:35.959
Alrighty, I have a couple more questions here in Slido

00:43:35.959 --> 00:43:38.520
and some of them kind of pertain to each other.

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:39.760
One that I really liked was,

00:43:39.800 --> 00:43:42.199
what are some of the most impactful ways

00:43:42.199 --> 00:43:45.280
that you've seen AI make a difference to your stakeholders?

00:43:49.479 --> 00:43:52.919
So my stakeholders are

00:43:54.919 --> 00:43:58.360
effectively sales leadership inside Microsoft.

00:44:00.320 --> 00:44:04.520
We have people with neurodiversity,

00:44:04.520 --> 00:44:06.199
their neurodivergent conditions.

00:44:06.199 --> 00:44:08.919
We've got people who are incredibly time-strapped.

00:44:08.919 --> 00:44:11.719
We have huge areas of responsibility,

00:44:11.719 --> 00:44:16.719
like kind of billions of pounds

00:44:17.600 --> 00:44:20.360
or billions of dollars of revenue every year

00:44:20.360 --> 00:44:23.000
that they're kind of trying to get

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:26.120
25% plus year-on-year growth in.

00:44:26.120 --> 00:44:31.120
So they're a highly capable group,

00:44:31.479 --> 00:44:35.199
but they are facing a tremendous amount of change

00:44:35.199 --> 00:44:37.000
on a continuous basis.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:42.000
And like me, it's not that we're triple booked,

00:44:42.760 --> 00:44:46.120
we get to choose between three sessions at a time,

00:44:46.120 --> 00:44:47.719
where are we going to have impact

00:44:48.919 --> 00:44:51.840
in terms of like calendar management?

00:44:51.840 --> 00:44:55.399
So it's actually just the base, like co-pilots

00:44:56.320 --> 00:45:01.320
is having a really great impact on them,

00:45:01.520 --> 00:45:05.040
helping be able to digest emails more quickly,

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:10.040
being able to get a quick kind of TLDR

00:45:10.679 --> 00:45:13.000
on a presentation before they work out

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:16.320
where they need to go to go look at specifics

00:45:16.320 --> 00:45:18.239
that they need to drill into.

00:45:18.239 --> 00:45:20.959
It's helping them never start from a white page.

00:45:20.959 --> 00:45:23.280
It's helping them catch up on meetings,

00:45:23.280 --> 00:45:25.800
find out what actions they've been assigned,

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:28.399
things that they haven't been able to get to,

00:45:28.399 --> 00:45:30.959
helping them analyze how they speak

00:45:30.959 --> 00:45:35.959
and convey information and things like that.

00:45:36.399 --> 00:45:40.919
So it's just like AI is having

00:45:40.919 --> 00:45:44.360
a pervasive productivity benefit

00:45:44.360 --> 00:45:47.840
that's enabling all of my key stakeholders

00:45:47.840 --> 00:45:50.320
to achieve more, which is super duper cool.

00:45:52.159 --> 00:45:54.000
We have a great follow-up to that,

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:55.000
because some of these Slido ones

00:45:55.000 --> 00:45:56.600
were sort of in the same vein.

00:45:56.600 --> 00:45:58.239
And the question is,

00:45:58.239 --> 00:46:01.280
how do you see AI impacting data science roles?

00:46:01.280 --> 00:46:03.360
Do you think it will replace jobs

00:46:03.360 --> 00:46:06.159
or impact on the skills that data scientists

00:46:06.159 --> 00:46:07.120
are going to need?

00:46:09.399 --> 00:46:13.159
So this will partly depend on

00:46:13.159 --> 00:46:16.239
what people's definitions of AI are.

00:46:16.239 --> 00:46:20.439
But I think generative AI

00:46:23.399 --> 00:46:26.199
has some amazing advancements

00:46:26.199 --> 00:46:29.040
on natural language processing

00:46:29.040 --> 00:46:33.040
and how we can interact in a multimodal capability

00:46:33.040 --> 00:46:35.879
is really groundbreaking.

00:46:37.639 --> 00:46:42.639
And I think we should all invest some time

00:46:43.280 --> 00:46:45.840
in knowing how we can leverage

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:49.080
whether it's large language models

00:46:49.080 --> 00:46:50.719
or small language models

00:46:50.719 --> 00:46:53.120
and how you can consume these things.

00:46:53.840 --> 00:46:57.520
Because they can change our interfaces.

00:46:57.520 --> 00:46:59.919
They can start supporting some reasoning

00:46:59.919 --> 00:47:02.600
and co-generation for us.

00:47:02.600 --> 00:47:07.600
But I don't see it replacing data scientists.

00:47:11.760 --> 00:47:14.239
It might replace some of the coding

00:47:14.239 --> 00:47:16.000
we do as data scientists.

00:47:16.800 --> 00:47:19.679
And I think of this kind of the same way.

00:47:20.520 --> 00:47:23.239
And I've always been quite dirty about these things.

00:47:23.239 --> 00:47:26.679
Like low code interfaces to data science.

00:47:26.679 --> 00:47:29.639
So like we had Azure Machine Learning Studio,

00:47:29.639 --> 00:47:31.280
you drag and drop,

00:47:31.280 --> 00:47:34.080
and you can put a bunch of boxes next to each other.

00:47:34.080 --> 00:47:35.800
And you go, hey, I've got a model.

00:47:35.800 --> 00:47:38.479
I don't understand it, but I've got something.

00:47:38.479 --> 00:47:39.919
You can now call an API.

00:47:41.840 --> 00:47:45.760
But the data scientist value for me

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:49.800
isn't how they solve the problem.

00:47:49.800 --> 00:47:52.479
It's how they help people understand

00:47:52.479 --> 00:47:53.800
and define the problem

00:47:55.399 --> 00:47:57.360
and bring the insight to light.

00:47:58.679 --> 00:48:00.520
So I think we might change.

00:48:00.520 --> 00:48:04.719
Like we might all write less code.

00:48:04.719 --> 00:48:07.959
We might be able to get the code part solved sooner.

00:48:07.959 --> 00:48:11.479
But our merits in understanding domains,

00:48:11.959 --> 00:48:16.959
turning that into scoped challenges and problem statements,

00:48:16.959 --> 00:48:21.959
and working out the appropriate steps to solve that

00:48:21.959 --> 00:48:25.840
with solid quality outcomes,

00:48:25.840 --> 00:48:27.239
that isn't gonna change.

00:48:28.679 --> 00:48:31.159
The what won't change, but the how might.

00:48:34.600 --> 00:48:35.800
Thank you.

00:48:35.800 --> 00:48:39.760
So a question that we love getting asked a lot

00:48:39.760 --> 00:48:42.439
and a question that we love getting to ask here

00:48:42.439 --> 00:48:44.879
at the Hangout is,

00:48:44.879 --> 00:48:47.159
is there a piece of career advice

00:48:47.159 --> 00:48:49.679
that you've received over your career

00:48:49.679 --> 00:48:51.479
or that you've given somebody

00:48:51.479 --> 00:48:53.120
that you'd like to share with us?

00:48:56.360 --> 00:49:01.360
I'd like to share one that took me years to break out of,

00:49:03.800 --> 00:49:07.919
which I think probably a lot of women get,

00:49:07.919 --> 00:49:10.639
which was I started a new job.

00:49:11.600 --> 00:49:15.800
I did something really, really impressive

00:49:15.800 --> 00:49:17.840
within my first week and sent an email

00:49:17.840 --> 00:49:21.479
and said I've done X, Y, Z to solve the problem.

00:49:21.479 --> 00:49:23.840
And my manager at the time said,

00:49:23.840 --> 00:49:27.120
no, no, not I, say we.

00:49:27.120 --> 00:49:29.639
The team did something.

00:49:29.639 --> 00:49:32.199
Well, the team wasn't actually involved,

00:49:32.199 --> 00:49:35.760
but I kind of got into this habit

00:49:35.760 --> 00:49:39.080
of giving away my impact.

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:41.639
Now, it's not that you need to brag

00:49:41.639 --> 00:49:44.439
and shout to the world like I'm amazing

00:49:44.439 --> 00:49:46.840
and like overhype everything you do,

00:49:48.520 --> 00:49:51.439
but you need to recognize

00:49:51.439 --> 00:49:54.679
when you're making a positive impact

00:49:54.679 --> 00:49:59.679
and reflect on how can I make more of that impact

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:02.080
based on the hard work I've already done?

00:50:03.000 --> 00:50:08.000
And a lot of that is actually less about you doing more

00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:15.199
and more about enabling other people

00:50:15.199 --> 00:50:17.600
to do things with what you've done.

00:50:17.600 --> 00:50:21.919
So it involves education, knowledge transfer,

00:50:21.919 --> 00:50:26.919
re-templating things, turning things into micro content,

00:50:27.280 --> 00:50:29.959
setting up a set of scheduled emails

00:50:29.959 --> 00:50:31.840
so that somebody actually reads it,

00:50:32.600 --> 00:50:33.760
they read it five times.

00:50:35.600 --> 00:50:37.560
And that's something that I think,

00:50:37.560 --> 00:50:42.560
I wish I hadn't have gotten effectively a code smell

00:50:43.280 --> 00:50:45.560
into my ways of working.

00:50:45.560 --> 00:50:47.959
And I think we should all think,

00:50:47.959 --> 00:50:50.159
how are you adding value?

00:50:50.159 --> 00:50:52.879
Be clear on how you're adding value

00:50:52.879 --> 00:50:57.840
and then use that information to pursue more impact

00:50:57.840 --> 00:51:00.239
and more scale of your value.

00:51:02.120 --> 00:51:05.120
I really, really appreciate that advice.

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:07.639
